description:
Create the `TasksDialog` component for agent-scoped task viewing and add a "Tasks" button to the agent detail page.

## TasksDialog

File: `apps/client/src/layers/features/tasks/ui/TasksDialog.tsx`

```typescript
import { Dialog, DialogContent, DialogHeader, DialogTitle } from '@/layers/shared/ui';
import { TasksList } from './TasksList';
import { Zap, Plus } from 'lucide-react';
import { Button } from '@/layers/shared/ui';

interface TasksDialogProps {
  /** Agent ID to filter tasks by. */
  agentId: string;
  /** Display name of the agent (for the dialog title). */
  agentName: string;
  /** Whether the dialog is open. */
  open: boolean;
  /** Callback when the dialog open state changes. */
  onOpenChange: (open: boolean) => void;
}

/**
 * Agent-scoped task dialog.
 *
 * Displays tasks filtered by a specific agent. Used on the agent detail page
 * to show and manage tasks for that agent without navigating away.
 */
export function TasksDialog({ agentId, agentName, open, onOpenChange }: TasksDialogProps) {
  return (
    <Dialog open={open} onOpenChange={onOpenChange}>
      <DialogContent className="max-w-2xl">
        <DialogHeader>
          <DialogTitle className="flex items-center gap-2">
            <Zap className="h-4 w-4" />
            Tasks for {agentName}
          </DialogTitle>
        </DialogHeader>
        <div className="max-h-[60vh] overflow-auto">
          <TasksList agentId={agentId} />
        </div>
        <div className="flex justify-end pt-2">
          <Button size="sm" variant="outline">
            <Plus className="mr-1.5 h-4 w-4" />
            New Task
          </Button>
        </div>
      </DialogContent>
    </Dialog>
  );
}
```

The dialog uses `TasksList` with the `agentId` prop to pre-filter tasks. It includes a "New Task" button scoped to the agent.

## Agent detail page integration

In the agent detail page (find the component — likely in `apps/client/src/layers/features/agent-settings/` or `apps/client/src/layers/widgets/agents/`), add a "Tasks" button:

```typescript
import { Zap } from 'lucide-react';
import { TasksDialog } from '@/layers/features/tasks';
import { useTasks } from '@/layers/entities/tasks';
import { useState } from 'react';

// Inside the agent detail component:
const [tasksDialogOpen, setTasksDialogOpen] = useState(false);
const { data: tasks = [] } = useTasks();
const agentTaskCount = tasks.filter((t) => t.agentId === agent.id).length;

// Render the button (in the agent's action area):
<Button variant="outline" size="sm" onClick={() => setTasksDialogOpen(true)}>
  <Zap className="mr-1.5 h-4 w-4" />
  Tasks
  {agentTaskCount > 0 && (
    <Badge variant="secondary" className="ml-1.5">
      {agentTaskCount}
    </Badge>
  )}
</Button>

<TasksDialog
  agentId={agent.id}
  agentName={agent.name}
  open={tasksDialogOpen}
  onOpenChange={setTasksDialogOpen}
/>
```

The button shows a count badge if the agent has tasks.

## System agent behavior

For Damon (system agent), the agent detail page should show the same Tasks button. The dialog shows global tasks filtered by `agentId: 'damon'`. The delete option should NOT appear for Damon's tasks in the dialog (since Damon is a system agent — though individual tasks can be deleted; just Damon itself cannot be deleted).

## Tests

Create `apps/client/src/layers/features/tasks/__tests__/TasksDialog.test.tsx`:

1. Test dialog renders with correct title including agent name
2. Test TasksList is rendered with the agentId filter
3. Test "New Task" button is present
4. Test dialog opens and closes via onOpenChange
5. Test task count badge shows correct number on the trigger button

## Acceptance Criteria
- `TasksDialog` renders a dialog with agent-scoped `TasksList`
- Agent detail page has a "Tasks" button with count badge
- Clicking the button opens `TasksDialog`
- Tasks in the dialog are filtered by the agent's ID
- Works for both regular agents and Damon (system agent)
- All tests pass
